<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 13:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2a5ea550630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>13.</label.designator><headtext>Weight and Sufficiency of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7219dbb682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>13:5.</label.designator><headtext>Positive and negative testimony</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Positive testimony is direct evidence that says that a thing did or did not happen. <eos/><bos/>Negative testimony says that the witness did not see or know of an event&apos;s having transpired and is considered circumstantial evidence.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bd9bc5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“The existence of a fact testified to by one positive witness is to be believed, rather than that such fact did not exist because many other witnesses who had the same opportunity of observation swear that they did not see or know of its having existed. <eos/><bos/>This rule shall not apply when two parties have equal facilities for seeing or hearing a thing and one swears that it occurred while the other swears that it did not.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bd9bc5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] The trial court&apos;s exercise of its discretion may be measured by its oral statements, and they may be considered as positive evidence of such exercise.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bd9bc5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The jury, in its evaluation of credibility, may choose to give greater weight to negative testimony.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bd9bc5374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7bd9bc5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-serial-number="1881014711" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="I38e143f174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">McConnell v. State, 67 Ga. 633, 1881 WL 3448 (1881)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bd9bc5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-14-7" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I38e1e03074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-14-7</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bd9bc5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-serial-number="2041471617" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I38e22e5274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Dixon v. State, 341 Ga. App. 255, 800 S.E.2d 11 (2017)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bd9bc5374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-serial-number="1944103682" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I38e2ca9274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Atlanta &amp; W. P. R. Co. v. Twedell, 70 Ga. App. 812, 29 S.E.2d 668 (1944)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-serial-number="1958121648" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I38e2ca9574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ellis v. Southern Ry. Co., 96 Ga. App. 687, 101 S.E.2d 230 (1957)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017249" w-serial-number="1974127880" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I38e2ca9874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hogan v. Louisville &amp; Nashville R. Co., 130 Ga. App. 638, 204 S.E.2d 348 (1974)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 13:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
